liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The national anti-scam centre is warning fraudsters are targeting fans on social media, offering fake ticket sales and fake live-stream links to matches. The consumer watchdog, the ACCC, is reminding consumers to only buy from authorised ticket sellers, and to double-check a streaming site before entering any payment details to watch the game. "We are already seeing initial reports of scam activity, particularly on Facebook, where scammers are responding to posts from people looking for tickets and using compromised accounts to sell non-existent tickets," ACCC deputy chair Catriona Lowe says. "There have also been reports of scammers claiming there is a problem with the payment and asking for it to be made again."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Matildas fans are being urged to be wary of scammers ahead of tonight's game

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: North Korean leader Kim Jong Un and Russian President Vladimir Putin have exchanged letters pledging to develop their ties into what Kim called a "long-standing strategic relationship", North Korean state media says. The letters mark the 78th anniversary of Korea's liberation from Japan's 1910-45 colonial rule, which is also celebrated as a national holiday in South Korea. In his letter to Putin, Kim reportedly says the two countries' friendship was forged in World War II with victory over Japan and is now "fully demonstrating their invincibility and might in the struggle to smash the imperialists' arbitrary practices and hegemony". "The two countries will always emerge victorious, strongly supporting and cooperating with each other in the course of achieving their common goal and cause," he reportedly says. The United States has accused North Korea of providing weapons to Russia for its war in Ukraine, including artillery shells, shoulder-fired rockets and missiles. Pyongyang and Moscow have denied any arms transactions.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Kim Jong Un and Vladimir Putin exchange letters promising to strengthen ties

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese is hoping there will be constructive conversations on housing supply at today's national cabinet meeting. The meeting will focus on what can be done to ensure more homes are built, through land release, zoning and planning. Discussions on renters' rights will also take place. Albanese said yesterday that he was looking forward to a positive discussion with state and territory leaders. "We all know that housing supply is the key — we all know as well that renters need more rights, but it can't be done in a way that actually dampens housing supply." Meanwhile, welfare advocacy bodies are calling for immediate action to limit rent increases. The Greens also want national cabinet to provide solutions for renters in crisis in exchange for their support of the government's proposed $10 billion Housing Australia Future Fund. You can read more here:
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: As national cabinet meets today, there's growing pressure to fix Australia's housing crisis

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: If you're feeling the squeeze of Australian interest rates, with a 4.1 per cent cash rate, spare a thought for borrowers across the ditch, where the RBNZ has raised the cash rate to 5.5 per cent. The Kiwi central bank unveils its latest policy decision at 12pm AEST and is forecast to keep rates on hold but that doesn't mean the pain is over for home owners. Economists at the Commonwealth Bank's NZ arm ASB expect the cash rate, which has been at its current level since May, to now remain on hold until mid-next year, when it is tipping cuts to begin. However, CBA senior economist Kristina Clifton notes, "there is still plenty of monetary tightening to filter through to the NZ economy". "Around 90 per cent of mortgages in NZ are taken at fixed rates. "Fixed rate mortgages shelter the borrower from interest rate increases until the fixed term expires," Ms Clifton writes. "The effective interest rate on outstanding mortgages has risen, but at just over 5 per cent, it is still below the RBNZ’s official cash rate." Take a look at this chart: That's what you can see on the red line above — it's still below the official cash rate. By comparison, the yellow line, showing new fixed loan rates, is much higher. So as people roll off the rates indicated by the red line, they'll be facing a jump up to the yellow or green lines on the chart. "As more fixed rate loans expire and roll on to much higher fixed or variable interest rates household spending is likely to slow and reduce the pressure on inflation," Ms Clifton says. So while the RBNZ might not raise any further, NZ borrowers are unlikely to feel rates relief for some time.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: NZ rates tipped to stay on hold but hit still to flow through

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Hello, Stephanie Chalmers here to take you through markets this Wednesday. It was red across the boards in Europe and the US, while oil prices also fell sharply. And it looks like the ASX will follow, with futures down more than 1 per cent. Behind the negativity? Some stronger-than-expected data out of the US, showing retail sales increased by 0.7 per cent in July, raised concerns that the Federal Reserve may need to hike interest rates further to tame inflation. Meanwhile, worries about China's economic health weighed on oil prices, with Brent crude down more than 1 per cent, despite surprise rate cuts from Beijing yesterday. Locally, reporting season rolls on, with quite a few results today: Transurban Dexus Endeavour Group Mirvac Bapcor Seven West Media And at midday AEST, the Reserve Bank of New Zealand will deliver its latest interest rate decision, with the cash rate tipped to stay on hold at 5.5 per cent. Stick with us for all the latest through the session!
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Good morning! But not for markets …
